        <main class="docs-body">
            <section id="getting-started">
                <h2>Getting Started</h2>
                <p>@brand is a self-hosted web hosting control panel. It manages domains, email, MySQL databases, DNS, SSL, file storage, billing and resellers from a single dashboard, and integrates directly with Nginx, MySQL, BIND9, Postfix/Dovecot and Let's Encrypt on Ubuntu.</p>
                <p>The fastest way to try it is the one-liner installer on a fresh Ubuntu 22.04 server. After install you log in as <code>admin</code>, configure your Stripe keys and hosting packages, and start creating accounts.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="requirements">
                <h2>Requirements</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>OS:</strong> Ubuntu 22.04 LTS (fresh server recommended)</li>
                    <li><strong>CPU:</strong> 1 core minimum (2+ recommended)</li>
                    <li><strong>RAM:</strong> 1 GB minimum (2 GB+ recommended)</li>
                    <li><strong>Disk:</strong> 10 GB minimum</li>
                    <li><strong>Access:</strong> root (or sudo) and a domain name pointed at the server IP</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="install">
                <h2>One-liner Install</h2>
                <p>Run this on a fresh Ubuntu 22.04 server as root. The installer is interactive — it asks for your panel domain, admin credentials and which optional services (email, DNS, FTP, phpMyAdmin) to enable.</p>
                <pre><code>curl -fsSL https://get.srxpanel.com/install.sh | bash</code></pre>
                <p>The script installs Nginx, MySQL, PHP (7.4–8.3), the .NET 9 runtime, Certbot and your selected services, provisions the database, deploys the panel as a <code>systemd</code> service, configures the Nginx reverse proxy with a Let's Encrypt certificate, and hardens the box with UFW and Fail2ban.</p>
                <div class="callout"><i class="bi bi-info-circle"></i> When it finishes, the installer prints your panel URL, admin password and the location of the saved MySQL root credentials (<code>/etc/srxpanel/db.conf</code>).</div>
            </section>

            <section id="docker">
                <h2>Docker</h2>
                <p>Prefer containers? Use the bundled Compose stack (panel + MySQL + Nginx + Certbot):</p>
                <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/srxpanel/srxpanel
cd srxpanel/docker
cp .env.example .env
nano .env          # set domain, passwords, Stripe keys
docker compose up -d</code></pre>
                <p>Named volumes persist the database, panel data and SSL certificates across restarts. Health checks and an auto-restart policy are configured for every service.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="update">
                <h2>Updating</h2>
                <p>Update in place from the server shell:</p>
                <pre><code>curl -fsSL https://get.srxpanel.com/update.sh | bash</code></pre>
                <p>Or from the panel itself under <strong>Admin → Updates</strong>, where you can view the changelog, apply updates with one click, review update history and enable automatic updates. The panel version is exposed at <code>/api/health</code>.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="config">
                <h2>Configuration</h2>
                <p>Runtime configuration lives in <code>appsettings.json</code> (and <code>appsettings.Production.json</code> on a server). Key settings:</p>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Key</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td><code>ConnectionStrings:DefaultConnection</code></td><td>Database connection string (SQLite by default)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>Version</code> / <code>UpdateChannel</code></td><td>Panel version and release channel (<code>stable</code>/<code>beta</code>)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>SimulationMode</code></td><td>When <code>true</code>, service commands are logged but not executed (dev/Windows)</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>Stripe:*</code></td><td>Publishable/secret/webhook keys for billing</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>Panel:Hostname</code></td><td>The panel's public hostname</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>Panel:LetsEncryptEmail</code></td><td>Email used for SSL certificate registration</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>Panel:Smtp:*</code></td><td>Outbound email server for panel notifications</td></tr>
                        <tr><td><code>Panel:MySql:*</code></td><td>MySQL root connection used to provision databases</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
                <p>Platform-level options (branding, fees, trial length, registration mode, update channel) are editable in the UI under <strong>Admin → Platform Settings</strong>.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="api">
                <h2>REST API</h2>
                <p>Clients authenticate by exchanging an API key (created under <strong>API Access</strong>) for a JWT:</p>
                <pre><code>curl -X POST https://panel.example.com/api/v1/auth/token \
  -H "X-API-Key: sk_live_..."
# → { "access_token": "...", "token_type": "Bearer", "expires_in": 86400 }</code></pre>
                <p>Then call resource endpoints with the bearer token:</p>
                <table>
                    <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Endpoint</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr><td>GET</td><td><code>/api/v1/account</code></td><td>Current account details</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GET/POST</td><td><code>/api/v1/domains</code></td><td>List / create domains</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>DELETE</td><td><code>/api/v1/domains/{id}</code></td><td>Delete a domain</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GET/POST</td><td><code>/api/v1/emails</code></td><td>List / create mailboxes</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GET/POST</td><td><code>/api/v1/databases</code></td><td>List / create databases</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GET</td><td><code>/api/v1/stats/usage</code></td><td>Resource usage summary</td></tr>
                        <tr><td>GET</td><td><code>/api/health</code></td><td>Public service health &amp; version</td></tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </section>

            <section id="whmcs">
                <h2>WHMCS &amp; Blesta Module</h2>
                <p>Automate provisioning from your billing system. Endpoints authenticate with an <code>X-API-Key</code> header and are rate-limited to 100 requests/minute.</p>
                <pre><code>POST /api/v1/whmcs/CreateAccount
POST /api/v1/whmcs/SuspendAccount
POST /api/v1/whmcs/UnsuspendAccount
POST /api/v1/whmcs/TerminateAccount
POST /api/v1/whmcs/ChangePackage</code></pre>
                <p>The full endpoint reference, response formats and a ready-made PHP module are on the <a href="/Docs/Whmcs" style="color:#79c0ff;">WHMCS integration page</a> inside the panel.</p>
            </section>

            <section id="reseller">
                <h2>Reseller Guide</h2>
                <p>Resellers get their own branded control panel and sell hosting under their own name:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Allocation:</strong> the admin assigns each reseller disk, bandwidth, client and domain limits.</li>
                    <li><strong>Packages:</strong> resellers create their own hosting packages and public pricing.</li>
                    <li><strong>White-label:</strong> custom panel title, logo, colours and (optionally) a custom domain.</li>
                    <li><strong>Billing:</strong> prepaid balance or postpaid invoicing, with a configurable platform fee and multi-currency support.</li>
                    <li><strong>Clients:</strong> resellers create and impersonate their own clients without seeing other tenants.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="troubleshooting">
                <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
                <h3>The panel won't start</h3>
                <pre><code>systemctl status srxpanel
journalctl -u srxpanel -n 100 --no-pager</code></pre>
                <h3>Check overall health</h3>
                <pre><code>curl -s https://panel.example.com/api/health | jq</code></pre>
                <h3>SSL certificate failed to issue</h3>
                <p>Confirm the panel domain's DNS <code>A</code> record points at the server and ports 80/443 are open in UFW, then re-run <code>certbot --nginx -d panel.example.com</code>.</p>
                <h3>Reset the admin password</h3>
                <p>Re-run the installer's seed step, or update the password hash directly in the database. Full recovery steps are documented in the repository README.</p>
            </section>
        </main>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
